4.1 Threat Detection Algorithm


Input:
    Telemetry data T = {signal_strength, packet_loss, latency,
                        frequency_variation, encryption}

Output:
    Predicted threat type (Normal, DoS, Jamming, Spoofing, MITM)
    Anomaly status

Step 1: Collect telemetry parameters from satellite communication

Step 2: Preprocess the data
        • Normalize telemetry features
        • Remove invalid or missing values

Step 3: Feature extraction
        F = {signal_strength, packet_loss, latency,
             frequency_variation, encryption}

Step 4: Apply Random Forest classifier
        threat_type = RF_Model.predict(F)

Step 5: Perform anomaly detection using Isolation Forest
        anomaly = IF_Model.predict(F)

Step 6: Apply Deep Learning model for advanced detection
        deep_result = DL_Model.predict(F)

Step 7: Evaluate results
        IF anomaly == -1
            anomaly_status = "Anomaly Attack Detected"
        ELSE
            anomaly_status = "Normal Traffic"

Step 8: Display results in cybersecurity dashboard

Step 9: Visualize attack statistics, telemetry graphs,
        and satellite orbit simulation

Return threat_type, anomaly_status



The proposed system utilizes machine learning and deep learning models to detect cyber threats in satellite communication networks. The detection process is summarized in Algorithm 1.

5. Dataset Description

The dataset used in this study is a synthetic satellite telemetry dataset generated to simulate normal and malicious communication patterns within a satellite network environment. Since real satellite telemetry data is often restricted due to security and privacy concerns, synthetic data generation was employed to model realistic telemetry behavior.

The dataset contains telemetry parameters that represent communication characteristics between satellites and ground stations.

Dataset Features
Feature	Description
Signal Strength	Represents the received signal power from satellite communication
Packet Loss	Percentage of packets lost during transmission
Latency	Communication delay between satellite and receiver
Frequency Variation	Variation in signal frequency caused by interference or attack
Encryption Status	Indicates whether communication is encrypted
Attack Type	Label representing the type of cyber attack
Attack Categories

The dataset simulates multiple types of cyber threats:

Attack Type	Description
Normal	Legitimate satellite communication
DoS	Denial of Service attack disrupting signal communication
Jamming	Signal interference attack
Spoofing	Fake satellite signal injection
MITM	Man-in-the-Middle attack intercepting communication

The dataset is used to train and evaluate machine learning and deep learning models for detecting abnormal satellite communication behavior.

6. Results and Discussion

The proposed system successfully detects multiple types of cyber attacks in the simulated satellite communication environment. Experimental evaluation shows that the Random Forest model achieves high classification accuracy in identifying attack types.

The anomaly detection model effectively identifies unusual telemetry patterns, providing an additional layer of security monitoring. The deep learning model further enhances the system’s ability to detect sophisticated attack patterns.

The cybersecurity dashboard allows real-time monitoring of satellite telemetry data and visualizes attack statistics through interactive charts and graphs.

7. Conclusion

This research presents a machine learning and deep learning based framework for detecting cyber threats in satellite communication systems. The proposed Satellite Threat Simulation System integrates threat detection algorithms, anomaly detection, and an interactive visualization dashboard.

The system demonstrates the potential of artificial intelligence techniques in improving the security and monitoring of satellite networks. Future work may focus on integrating real satellite telemetry data, enhancing real-time attack detection, and deploying the system on cloud platforms for large-scale monitoring.

